📘 Functions in DSA
🟢 Introduction

A function is a reusable block of code that performs a specific task.

In DSA, functions help break complex problems into smaller, manageable parts.

🟢 Why Functions are Important in DSA

Functions are used to:

Improve code readability
Reduce repetition (reusability)
Simplify complex algorithms
Enable modular programming

👉 Every algorithm in DSA is basically a combination of functions.

🟢 Basic Structure of a Function
🔹 Syntax (C)
return_type function_name(parameters) {
    // function body
    return value;
}
🟢 Example Function
🔹 C
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
🔹 Java
static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
🟢 Function Components
Component	Description
Return Type	Type of value returned
Function Name	Identifier
Parameters	Input values
Body	Logic of function
Return Statement	Sends result back
🟢 Types of Functions
🔹 1. No Parameters, No Return
void greet() {
    printf("Hello");
}
🔹 2. Parameters, No Return
void printSum(int a, int b) {
    printf("%d", a + b);
}
🔹 3. No Parameters, Return Value
int getNumber() {
    return 5;
}
🔹 4. Parameters & Return Value (Most Important ⭐)
int multiply(int a, int b) {
    return a * b;
}
🟢 Function Call
int result = add(5, 3);

👉 Execution flow:

Call function
Pass arguments
Execute function body
Return result
🟢 Functions in DSA Algorithms
Example: Find Maximum
int max(int a, int b) {
    if (a > b)
        return a;
    else
        return b;
}
🟢 Pass by Value vs Reference
🔹 Pass by Value
Copy of variable is passed
Original value not changed
🔹 Pass by Reference
Address is passed
Original value can change
Example (C)
void update(int *x) {
    *x = 10;
}
🟢 Recursion (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)

A function calling itself.

Example:
int factorial(int n) {
    if (n == 0)
        return 1;
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}
🟢 Advantages of Functions

✔ Code reusability
✔ Modular design
✔ Easy debugging
✔ Better readability

🟢 Common Mistakes ❌
Missing return statement
Infinite recursion
Wrong data types
Not passing correct arguments
🟢 Conclusion

Functions are essential in DSA for writing efficient and modular code.
They form the base for solving complex algorithmic problems.
